{
  "texts": [
    "Building a possibility frame on a complete Boolean lattice-minus the bottom element-makes it easy to deal with the set P of admissible propositions.",
    "For if ⟨S, ⊑⟩ is a poset obtained from a complete Boolean lattice by deleting the bottom element, then the regular open sets in the downset topology on ⟨S, ⊑⟩ are just ∅ and each principal downset ↓x = {x ′ ∈ S | x ′ ⊑ x} for x ∈ S (see Fact 4.49).",
    "Thus, the regular open sets in the downset topology on ⟨RO(R) \\ {∅}, ⊆⟩ are ∅ and each ↓O= {O ′ ∈ RO(R) \\ {∅} | O ′ ⊆ O}.We noted above how a regular open set can be canonically encoded as a nonempty set of pairs of real numbers.",
    "We will take as the possibilities of our frame F not only every nonempty regular open set of reals, but also every nonempty set of pairs of reals.",
    "Thus, letS = (RO(R) ∪ ℘(R 2)) \\ {∅}.We will write 'O', 'O ′ ', etc., for elements of RO(R) \\ {∅}, and 'σ', 'σ ′ ', 'τ ', etc., for elements of ℘(R 2) \\ {∅}.The refinement relation ⊑ in our frame F will be ⊆."
  ]
}